pr_body:
This work was part of my Google Summer of Code project. The following are the major contributions of the project.

- Addition of multiple negatives ranking loss
- Addition of an example notebook for fine-tuning CLIP using multiple negatives ranking loss
pr_review_comments:
[{'comment_id': 977237241, 'comment_body': 'Will this work for unnormalized distances like L2? I think it might be better to either refactor the loss to work with distance instead of similarity or just raise a ValueError if the distance != "inner_product". ', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 9, 22, 6, 12, 49, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'owenvallis', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 977252828, 'comment_body': 'Is this just LogSumExp? If so, we have a version in https://github.com/tensorflow/similarity/blob/master/tensorflow_similarity/losses/utils.py#L141 

that version supports a mask along the diagonal and is numerically stable for small and large values.

We use it in the multi-sim loss https://github.com/tensorflow/similarity/blob/2821d07e7248c412384734b1592b94140754897d/tensorflow_similarity/losses/multisim_loss.py#L141', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 9, 22, 6, 33, 25, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'owenvallis', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 992146100, 'comment_body': "I agree negative distance is not an appropriate transformation for similarity in all cases. For now, I'll enforce inner_product.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 10, 11, 10, 32, 47, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'abhisharsinha', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 994048460, 'comment_body': 'So I checked https://arxiv.org/pdf/1705.00652.pdf and I think we want a minor change to the loss here. It currently includes the positives along the diagonal in the reduce_sum on line 55. We can avoid this and get better numerical stability using the [tfsim logsomexp](https://github.com/tensorflow/similarity/blob/master/tensorflow_similarity/losses/utils.py#L141). Then your loss becomes:

```
    pos_loss = tf.linalg.diag_part(pairwise_sim)
    diag_mask = tf.eye(pairwise_sim.shape[0])
    neg_loss = logsumexp(pairwise_sim,  diag_mask)
    examples_loss = -pos_loss + neg_loss
```', 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 10, 13, 2, 22, 47, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'owenvallis', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 996416087, 'comment_body': "Thanks, I'll incorporate this and push the changes", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 10, 16, 9, 29, 40, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'abhisharsinha', 'type': 'User'}, {'comment_id': 1002634041, 'comment_body': "We'll want to update this once we merge into to the dev branch.", 'comment_created': datetime.datetime(2022, 10, 23, 4, 52, 16, tzinfo=datetime.timezone.utc), 'commenter': 'owenvallis', 'type': 'User'}]
